bility to find adequate responses to the challenges of globalization. The book provides a detailed overview of how citizens in Europe are coping with a xenophobia fueled by their own sense of insecurity. The authors reconstruct the competing sociological reactions to migration in the forms of integration, assimilation and segregation. Hungary receives special attention: the data show that people living there are far less closed and xenophobic than they might seem through the prism of a media-instigated moral panic.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aImmigrantszEuropexPublic opinion. 0aImmigrantszEuropexSocial conditions. 0aNational characteristics, European. 0aNationalismzEurope. 0aXenophobiazEurope. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / European Studies.2bisacsh  aMigration, Nationalism, Values, European Union.1 aÖrkény, Antal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2021z97831107804990 cprintz978963386367140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633863664zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633863664/original  a978-3-11-078049-9 Central European University Press eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA